Random Forest

The main concept behind Random Forests is to generate many decision trees by sampling both, the observations and the variables. Observation are randomized by selecting same number of observations but allowing for observations to be selected again ( with replacement ). Variables are randomized by selecting a small number ( often referred to as m) compared to the total number of observations. Each tree in this forest is grown without any pruning. Pruning is the process of trimming the tree to avoid over-fitting. In this case we donât prune at all.

Now, when an input is provided, all the trees will vote on a given result and the outcome with the most votes will win. One often has to adjust the m to identify the optimal results.

Random Forest is a popular method for predictive analysis because it is fast and less likely to overfit. The observations are randomly selected ( with replacement ) the remaining dataset is referred to as âout of bagâ (OOB) data. This is the same idea as the Leave Out set. Random Forest will try to classify the OOB data and determine accuracy of the model. For this reason one does not have to perform any cross validation, because every time a tree is created, it goes through a round of assesment.

Variable importance

To calculate whether a variable is imporant you simply perform the following steps:

  • Count the number of correct predictions
  • For a given variable, simply randomize/shuffle the values and then count the number of correct prediction.
  • Repeat this in all tree for that one variable. The average difference of the predictions minus the correct predictions is the importance score of the variable.

Gini impurity is very similar to Entropy ( or the gain of information ) except the calculations are slightly different.

There are two popular packages to perform the analysis. One is the party package that we used earlier for Decision Trees, and there is also the randomForest package

Letâs also limit the variables we want to use.

specific_data = data[,c("alivestatus","grade","nodespos","nodesexam","size","pgr","er")]

Writing the randomForest model is the same as writing any other model, but first letâs make sure alivestatus is a factor. Also we will use the importance=T option to calculate how important each variable is.

specific_data$alivestatus = as.factor(specific_data$alivestatus)
library(randomForest)
## Warning: package 'randomForest' was built under R version 3.4.4
## randomForest 4.6-14
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
datarf = randomForest(alivestatus ~ ., data=specific_data, importance=T)
datarf
## 
## Call:
##  randomForest(formula = alivestatus ~ ., data = specific_data,      importance = T) 
##                Type of random forest: classification
##                      Number of trees: 500
## No. of variables tried at each split: 2
## 
##         OOB estimate of  error rate: 16.57%
## Confusion matrix:
##       0   1 class.error
## 0 11782 463  0.03781135
## 1  2023 732  0.73430127

There are some standard plots that are available in the results

plot(datarf, xlim=c(0,50))

The plot above shows that after almost 20 trees, the predictions stop getting better. The green line is the prediction of alive (0) patients and the red is the dead (1) patients. The black is the average.

varImpPlot(datarf)

The first plot shows how much accuracy is affected by changing the values in the different variable. Nodespos is the most important because changing its values alters the results the most.

The second plot shows a measurement that is similar to Information gain. Again nodespos has the most informative variable if the patient will live or die.

cForest() function

Letâs repeat the analysis using the cForest() function in the party package. cForest is much slower in creating and specially predicting using very deep trees so letâs just do 100 trees.

library("party")
## Warning: package 'party' was built under R version 3.4.4
## Loading required package: grid
## Loading required package: mvtnorm
## Loading required package: modeltools
## Loading required package: stats4
## Loading required package: strucchange
## Loading required package: zoo
## 
## Attaching package: 'zoo'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     as.Date, as.Date.numeric
## Loading required package: sandwich
dataparty.rf = cforest(alivestatus ~ grade + nodespos + nodesexam + size + pgr + er, 
                       data=specific_data,
                       controls=cforest_unbiased(ntree=100,mtry=2))
dataparty.rf
## 
##   Random Forest using Conditional Inference Trees
## 
## Number of trees:  100 
## 
## Response:  alivestatus 
## Inputs:  grade, nodespos, nodesexam, size, pgr, er 
## Number of observations:  15000

Letâs look at the results. Did this perform better than randomForest?

dataparty.rf.results = predict(dataparty.rf,OOB=TRUE)

table(dataparty.rf.results, specific_data$alivestatus)

## dataparty.rf.results     0     1
##                    0 11795  1990

We can also get the probabilities for the predictions.

dataparty.rf.results.prob = predict(dataparty.rf, OOB = T,type="prob")

Drawing a tree

The following code was obtained from stack exchange.

pt <- prettytree(dataparty.rf@ensemble[[1]],
                 names(dataparty.rf@data@get("input"))) 
nt <- new("BinaryTree") 
nt@tree <- pt 
nt@data <- dataparty.rf@data 
nt@responses <- dataparty.rf@responses 

plot(nt, type="simple")
